25 [34]. The Genitive of Quality is used with the same brachy— logy as the corresponding ablative (18): effusae clementiae, vi 30, 33 ademptae virilitatis, vi 31, 3.

26 [37]. In such phrases as the following, the genitive of gerund or gerundive shows a bold extension os the idea ‘ belonging to' :

(a) defining a noun : cuius apiscendae otium apud Rhodum . . . habuit, vi 20, 3; pecunia omittendae delationis, vi 30, 1 ; spatium exuendi pacta, xi 43, 1 ;

(b) used predicatively: quae conciliandae misericordiae vide- bantur, xi 3, 13 so Sall. Cat. 6, regium imperium initio conser- vandae libertatis atque augendae reipublicae suerat.

Ill. VERBS.

27 [38, 39]. Verbs of speaking, thinking, and even of motion are omitted with more freedom than in earlier classical Latin: haec (dixit), vi 2, 63 haec apud senatum (acta sunt), vi 10, 2.

Parts of esse, other than present indicative and infinitive‚ are omitted, even in dependent clauses: quae retinenda . . . (essent), xi 15, 33 quidquid Neronibus avitum (fuerit), xi 35, 2; also, in apodosis of conditional sentence, oppressa cunctantium dubitatio (erat), vi 43, 1; notice also the omission of fuisse aster a future participle, periturum, xi 3, 2.
